# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aws-elasticache
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aws-elasticache/amazon-elasticache] As a web service running in the computing cloud, Amazon ElastiCache is designed to simplify the setup, operation, and scaling of Valkey, Memcached, and Redis deployments.
[src:aws-elasticache/amazon-elasticache] Complex administration processes like patching software, backing up and restoring data sets and dynamically adding or removing capabilities are managed automatically.
[src:aws-elasticache/amazon-elasticache] Scaling ElastiCache resources can be performed by a single API call.
[src:aws-elasticache/amazon-elasticache] Amazon ElastiCache was first released on August 22, 2011, supporting memcached.
[src:aws-elasticache/amazon-elasticache] This was followed by support for reserved instances on April 5, 2012 and Redis on September 4, 2013.
[src:aws-elasticache/amazon-elasticache] Database limitations are often a bottleneck for application performance.
[src:aws-elasticache/amazon-elasticache] By placing Amazon ElastiCache between an application and its database tier, database operations can be accelerated.
[src:aws-elasticache/amazon-elasticache] Using ElastiCache for database performance acceleration can significantly reduce the infrastructure needed to support the database.
[src:aws-elasticache/amazon-elasticache] In many cases, the cost savings outweigh the cache costs.
[src:aws-elasticache/amazon-elasticache] Expedia was able to use ElastiCache to reduce provisioned DynamoDB capacity by 90%, reducing total database cost by 6x.
[src:aws-elasticache/amazon-elasticache] Using the Redis engine, ElastiCache can rapidly process time-series data, quickly selecting newest or oldest records or events within range of a point-in-time.
[src:aws-elasticache/amazon-elasticache] Leaderboards are an effective way to show a user quickly where they currently stand within a gamified system.
[src:aws-elasticache/amazon-elasticache] For systems with large numbers of gamers, calculating and publishing player ranks can be challenging.
[src:aws-elasticache/amazon-elasticache] Using Amazon ElastiCache with the Redis engine can enable high-speed at scale for leaderboards.
[src:aws-elasticache/amazon-elasticache] Some APIs only allow a limited number of requests per time period.
[src:aws-elasticache/amazon-elasticache] Amazon ElastiCache for Redis engine can use incremental counters and other tools to throttle API access to meet restrictions.
[src:aws-elasticache/amazon-elasticache] Programs can use incremental counters to limit allowed quantities, such as the maximum number of students enrolled in a course or ensuring a game has at least 2 but not more than 8 players.
[src:aws-elasticache/amazon-elasticache] Using counters can create a race condition where an operation is allowed because a counter was not updated promptly.
[src:aws-elasticache/amazon-elasticache] Using the ElastiCache for Redis atomic counter functions, where a single operation both checks and increments the counter's value, prevents race conditions.
[src:aws-elasticache/amazon-elasticache] ElastiCache for Redis supports publish-subscribe patterns, which enable the creation of chat rooms and message boards where messages are automatically distributed to interested users.
[src:aws-elasticache/amazon-elasticache] Amazon ElastiCache can use on-demand cache nodes or reserved cache nodes.
[src:aws-elasticache/amazon-elasticache] An efficient cache can significantly increase application's performance and user navigation speed.
[src:aws-elasticache/amazon-elasticache] Amazon CloudWatch exposes ElastiCache performance metrics that can be tracked.
[src:aws-elasticache/amazon-elasticache] Using the online management console is the simplest way to monitor ElastiCache with CloudWatch.
[src:aws-elasticache/amazon-elasticache] It allows to set up basic automated alerts and to get a visual picture of recent changes in individual metrics.
[src:aws-elasticache/amazon-elasticache] Metrics related to ElastiCache can also be retrieved using command lines.
[src:aws-elasticache/amazon-elasticache] It can be used for spot checks and ad hoc investigations.
[src:aws-elasticache/amazon-elasticache] The third way to collect ElastiCache metrics is via a dedicated monitoring tool integrating with Amazon CloudWatch.
[src:aws-elasticache/amazon-elasticache] As an AWS service, ElastiCache is designed to be accessed exclusively from within AWS, though it is possible to connect the service to applications and databases that are not hosted by AWS.
[src:aws-elasticache/amazon-elasticache] Other vendors provide cloud data cache services comparable to Amazon ElastiCache, including Azure Cache for Redis, Redis Ltd (company behind open source Redis and Redis Enterprise), Redis To Go, IBM Compose, Oracle Application Container Cloud Service, and Rackspace ObjectRocket.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] In computing, a **cache** (/kæʃ/ ⓘ *KASH*) is a hardware or software component that stores data so that future requests for that data can be served faster; the data stored in a cache might be the result of an earlier computation or a copy of data stored elsewhere.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] A **cache hit** occurs when the requested data can be found in a cache, while a **cache miss** occurs when it cannot.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] Cache hits are served by reading data from the cache, which is faster than recomputing a result or reading from a slower data store; thus, the more requests that can be served from the cache, the faster the system performs.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] To be cost-effective, caches must be relatively small.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] Nevertheless, caches are effective in many areas of computing because typical computer applications access data with a high degree of locality of reference.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] Such access patterns exhibit temporal locality, where data is requested that has been recently requested, and spatial locality, where data is requested that is stored near data that has already been requested.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] In memory design, there is an inherent trade-off between capacity and speed because larger capacity implies larger size and thus greater physical distances for signals to travel causing propagation delays.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] There is also a tradeoff between high-performance technologies such as SRAM and cheaper, easily mass-produced commodities such as DRAM, flash, or hard disks.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] The buffering provided by a cache benefits one or both of latency and throughput (bandwidth).
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] A larger resource incurs a significant latency for access – e.g. it can take hundreds of clock cycles for a modern 4 GHz processor to reach DRAM.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] This is mitigated by reading large chunks into the cache, in the hope that subsequent reads will be from nearby locations and can be read from the cache.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] Prediction or explicit prefetching can be used to guess where future reads will come from and make requests ahead of time; if done optimally, the latency is bypassed altogether.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] The use of a cache also allows for higher throughput from the underlying resource, by assembling multiple fine-grain transfers into larger, more efficient requests.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] In the case of DRAM circuits, the additional throughput may be gained by using a wider data bus.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] Hardware implements cache as a block of memory for temporary storage of data likely to be used again.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] Central processing units (CPUs), solid-state drives (SSDs) and hard disk drives (HDDs) frequently include hardware-based cache, while web browsers and web servers commonly rely on software caching.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] A cache is made up of a pool of entries.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] Each entry has associated *data*, which is a copy of the same data in some *backing store*.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] Each entry also has a *tag*, which specifies the identity of the data in the backing store of which the entry is a copy.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] When the cache client (a CPU, web browser, operating system) needs to access data presumed to exist in the backing store, it first checks the cache.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] If an entry can be found with a tag matching that of the desired data, the data in the entry is used instead.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] This situation is known as a **cache hit**.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] For example, a web browser program might check its local cache on disk to see if it has a local copy of the contents of a web page at a particular URL.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] In this example, the URL is the tag, and the content of the web page is the data.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] The percentage of accesses that result in cache hits is known as the **hit rate** or **hit ratio** of the cache.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] The alternative situation, when the cache is checked and found not to contain any entry with the desired tag, is known as a **cache miss**.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] This requires a more expensive access of data from the backing store.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] Once the requested data is retrieved, it is typically copied into the cache, ready for the next access.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] During a cache miss, some other previously existing cache entry is typically removed in order to make room for the newly retrieved data.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] The heuristic used to select the entry to replace is known as the replacement policy.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] One popular replacement policy, least recently used (LRU), replaces the oldest entry, the entry that was accessed less recently than any other entry.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] More sophisticated caching algorithms also take into account the frequency of use of entries.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] Cache writes must eventually be propagated to the backing store.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] The timing for this is governed by the *write policy*.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] A write-back cache is more complex to implement since it needs to track which of its locations have been written over and mark them as *dirty* for later writing to the backing store.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] The data in these locations are written back to the backing store only when they are evicted from the cache, a process referred to as a *lazy write*.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] For this reason, a read miss in a write-back cache may require two memory accesses to the backing store: one to write back the dirty data, and one to retrieve the requested data.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] Other policies may also trigger data write-back.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] The client may make many changes to data in the cache, and then explicitly notify the cache to write back the data.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] Consequently, a decision needs to be made for write misses: whether or not to load the data into the cache.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] Entities other than the cache may change the data in the backing store, in which case the copy in the cache may become out-of-date or *stale*.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] Alternatively, when the client updates the data in the cache, copies of that data in other caches will become stale.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] Communication protocols between the cache managers that keep the data consistent are associated with cache coherence.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] On a cache read miss, caches with a *demand paging policy* read the minimum amount from the backing store.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] A typical demand-paging virtual memory implementation reads one page of virtual memory (often 4 KB) from disk into the disk cache in RAM.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] A typical CPU reads a single L2 cache line of 128 bytes from DRAM into the L2 cache, and a single L1 cache line of 64 bytes from the L2 cache into the L1 cache.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] Caches with a prefetch input queue or more general *anticipatory paging policy* go further—they not only read the data requested, but guess that the next chunk or two of data will soon be required, and so prefetch that data into the cache ahead of time.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] Anticipatory paging is especially helpful when the backing store has a long latency to read the first chunk and much shorter times to sequentially read the next few chunks, such as disk storage and DRAM.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] A few operating systems go further with a loader that always pre-loads the entire executable into RAM.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] A few caches go even further, not only pre-loading an entire file, but also starting to load other related files that may soon be requested, such as the page cache associated with a prefetcher or the web cache associated with link prefetching.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] Small memories on or close to the CPU can operate faster than the much larger main memory.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] Most CPUs since the 1980s have used one or more caches, sometimes in cascaded levels; modern high-end embedded, desktop and server microprocessors may have as many as six types of cache (between levels and functions).
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] Some examples of caches with a specific function are the D-cache, I-cache and the translation lookaside buffer for the memory management unit (MMU).
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] Earlier graphics processing units (GPUs) often had limited read-only texture caches and used swizzling to improve 2D locality of reference.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] Cache misses would drastically affect performance, e.g. if mipmapping was not used.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] Caching was important to leverage 32-bit (and wider) transfers for texture data that was often as little as 4 bits per pixel.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] As GPUs advanced, supporting general-purpose computing on graphics processing units and compute kernels, they have developed progressively larger and increasingly general caches, including instruction caches for shaders, exhibiting functionality commonly found in CPU caches.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] These caches have grown to handle synchronization primitives between threads and atomic operations, and interface with a CPU-style MMU.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] Digital signal processors have similarly generalized over the years.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] Earlier designs used scratchpad memory fed by direct memory access; modern DSPs often include a very similar set of caches to a CPU (e.g.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] Modified Harvard architecture with shared L2, split L1 I-cache and D-cache).
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] A memory management unit (MMU) that fetches page table entries from main memory has a specialized cache, used for recording the results of virtual address to physical address translations.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] This specialized cache is called a translation lookaside buffer (TLB).
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] Information-centric networking (ICN) is an approach to evolve the Internet infrastructure away from a host-centric paradigm, based on perpetual connectivity and the end-to-end principle, to a network architecture in which the focal point is identified information.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] Due to the inherent caching capability of the nodes in an ICN, it can be viewed as a loosely connected network of caches, which has unique requirements for caching policies.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] However, ubiquitous content caching introduces the challenge to content protection against unauthorized access, which requires extra care and solutions.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] Unlike proxy servers, in ICN the cache is a network-level solution.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] Therefore, it has rapidly changing cache states and higher request arrival rates; moreover, smaller cache sizes impose different requirements on the content eviction policies.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] In particular, eviction policies for ICN should be fast and lightweight.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] Various cache replication and eviction schemes for different ICN architectures and applications have been proposed.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] The time aware least recently used (TLRU) is a variant of LRU designed for the situation where the stored contents in cache have a valid lifetime.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] The algorithm is suitable in network cache applications, such as ICN, content delivery networks (CDNs) and distributed networks in general.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] TLRU introduces a new term: time to use (TTU).
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] TTU is a time stamp on content which stipulates the usability time for the content based on the locality of the content and information from the content publisher.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] Owing to this locality-based time stamp, TTU provides more control to the local administrator to regulate in-network storage.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] In the TLRU algorithm, when a piece of content arrives, a cache node calculates the local TTU value based on the TTU value assigned by the content publisher.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] The local TTU value is calculated by using a locally defined function.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] Once the local TTU value is calculated the replacement of content is performed on a subset of the total content stored in cache node.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] The TLRU ensures that less popular and short-lived content should be replaced with incoming content.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] The least frequent recently used (LFRU) cache replacement scheme combines the benefits of LFU and LRU schemes.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] LFRU is suitable for network cache applications, such as ICN, CDNs and distributed networks in general.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] In LFRU, the cache is divided into two partitions called privileged and unprivileged partitions.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] The privileged partition can be seen as a protected partition.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] If content is highly popular, it is pushed into the privileged partition.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] Replacement of the privileged partition is done by first evicting content from the unprivileged partition, then pushing content from the privileged partition to the unprivileged partition, and finally inserting new content into the privileged partition.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] In the above procedure, the LRU is used for the privileged partition and an approximated LFU (ALFU) scheme is used for the unprivileged partition.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] The basic idea is to cache the locally popular content with the ALFU scheme and push the popular content to the privileged partition.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] In 2011, the use of smartphones with weather forecasting options was overly taxing AccuWeather servers; two requests from the same area would generate separate requests.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] An optimization by edge-servers to truncate the GPS coordinates to fewer decimal places meant that the cached results from a nearby query would be used.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] The number of to-the-server lookups per day dropped by half.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] While CPU caches are generally managed entirely by hardware, a variety of software manages other caches.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] The page cache in main memory is managed by the operating system kernel.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] While the disk buffer, which is an integrated part of the hard disk drive or solid state drive, is sometimes misleadingly referred to as *disk cache*, its main functions are write sequencing and read prefetching.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] High-end disk controllers often have their own on-board cache for the hard disk drive's data blocks.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] Finally, a fast local hard disk drive can also cache information held on even slower data storage devices, such as remote servers (web cache) or local tape drives or optical jukeboxes; such a scheme is the main concept of hierarchical storage management.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] Also, fast flash-based solid-state drives (SSDs) can be used as caches for slower rotational-media hard disk drives, working together as hybrid drives.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] Web browsers and web proxy servers, either locally or at the Internet service provider (ISP), employ web caches to store previous responses from web servers, such as web pages and images.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] Web caches reduce the amount of information that needs to be transmitted across the network, as information previously stored in the cache can often be re-used.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] This reduces bandwidth and processing requirements of the web server, and helps to improve responsiveness for users of the web.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] Another form of cache is P2P caching, where the files most sought for by peer-to-peer applications are stored in an ISP cache to accelerate P2P transfers.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] Similarly, decentralised equivalents exist, which allow communities to perform the same task for P2P traffic, for example, Corelli.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] A cache can store data that is computed on demand rather than retrieved from a backing store.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] Memoization is an optimization technique that stores the results of resource-consuming function calls within a lookup table, allowing subsequent calls to reuse the stored results and avoid repeated computation.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] It is related to the dynamic programming algorithm design methodology, which can also be thought of as a means of caching.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] A content delivery network (CDN) is a network of distributed servers that deliver pages and other web content to a user, based on the geographic locations of the user, the origin of the web page and the content delivery server.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] CDNs were introduced in the late 1990s as a way to speed up the delivery of static content, such as HTML pages, images and videos.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] By replicating content on multiple servers around the world and delivering it to users based on their location, CDNs can significantly improve the speed and availability of a website or application.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] When a user requests a piece of content, the CDN will check to see if it has a copy of the content in its cache.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] If it does, the CDN will deliver the content to the user from the cache.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] A cloud storage gateway is a hybrid cloud storage device that connects a local network to one or more cloud storage services, typically object storage services such as Amazon S3.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] It provides a cache for frequently accessed data, providing high speed local access to frequently accessed data in the cloud storage service.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] Cloud storage gateways also provide additional benefits such as accessing cloud object storage through traditional file serving protocols as well as continued access to cached data during connectivity outages.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] A DNS cache caches a mapping of domain names to IP addresses.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] Examples of services providing such caches include the BIND daemon and caching DNS resolver libraries.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] Write-through operation is common when operating over unreliable networks, because of the enormous complexity of the coherency protocol required between multiple write-back caches when communication is unreliable.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] For instance, web page caches and client-side caches for distributed file systems (like those in NFS or SMB) are typically read-only or write-through specifically to keep the network protocol simple and reliable.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] Web search engines also frequently make web pages they have indexed available from their cache.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] This can prove useful when web pages from a web server are temporarily or permanently inaccessible.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] Database caching can substantially improve the throughput of database applications, for example in the processing of indexes, data dictionaries, and frequently used subsets of data.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] A distributed cache uses networked hosts to provide scalability, reliability and performance to the application.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] The hosts can be co-located or spread over different geographical regions.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] Android Runtime and Common Language Runtime are examples that utilize storage-based JIT caches.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] GPU drivers usually utilize storage-based shader caches.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] The semantics of a *buffer* and a *cache* are not totally different; even so, there are fundamental differences in intent between the process of caching and the process of buffering.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] Fundamentally, caching realizes a performance increase for transfers of data that is being repeatedly transferred.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] With read caches, a data item must have been fetched from its residing location at least once in order for subsequent reads of the data item to realize a performance increase by virtue of being able to be fetched from the cache's faster intermediate storage rather than the data's residing location.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] Contrary to strict buffering, a caching process must adhere to a potentially distributed cache coherency protocol in order to maintain consistency between the cache's intermediate storage and the location where the data resides.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] Buffering, on the other hand, reduces the number of transfers for otherwise novel data amongst communicating processes, which amortizes the overhead involved for several small transfers over fewer, larger transfers.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] It also provides an intermediary for communicating processes that are incapable of direct transfers amongst each other, or ensures a minimum data size or representation required by at least one of the communicating processes involved in a transfer.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] With typical caching implementations, a data item that is read or written for the first time is effectively being buffered.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] Caching almost always involves some form of buffering, while strict buffering does not necessarily involve caching.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] A buffer is a temporary memory location that is traditionally used because CPU instructions cannot directly address data stored in peripheral devices.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] Thus, addressable memory is used as an intermediate stage.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] Additionally, such a buffer may be required when a large block of data is assembled or disassembled (as required by a storage device), or when data may be delivered in a different order than that in which it is produced.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] Also, a whole buffer of data is usually transferred sequentially (for example, to hard disk), so buffering itself sometimes increases transfer performance or reduces the variation or jitter of the transfer's latency as opposed to caching where the intent is to reduce the latency.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] These benefits are present even if the buffered data are written to the buffer once and read from the buffer once.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] A cache also increases transfer performance.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] A part of the increase similarly comes from the possibility that multiple small transfers will be combined into one large transfer.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] But the main performance gain occurs because there is a good chance that the same data will be read from cache multiple times, or that written data will soon be read.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] A cache's sole purpose is to reduce accesses to the underlying slower storage.
[src:aws-elasticache/cache-computing] Cache is also usually an abstraction layer that is designed to be invisible from the perspective of neighboring layers.
[src:aws-elasticache/in-memory-database] An **in-memory database** (**IMDb**, or **main memory database system** (**MMDB**) or **memory resident database**) is a database management system that primarily relies on main memory for computer data storage.
[src:aws-elasticache/in-memory-database] It is contrasted with database management systems that employ a disk storage mechanism.
[src:aws-elasticache/in-memory-database] In-memory databases are faster than disk-optimized databases because disk access is slower than memory access and the internal optimization algorithms are simpler and execute fewer CPU instructions.
[src:aws-elasticache/in-memory-database] Accessing data in memory eliminates seek time when querying the data, which provides faster and more predictable performance than disk.
[src:aws-elasticache/in-memory-database] Applications where response time is critical, such as those running telecommunications network equipment and mobile advertising networks, often use main-memory databases.
[src:aws-elasticache/in-memory-database] IMDBs have gained much traction, especially in the data analytics space, starting in the mid-2000s – mainly due to multi-core processors that can address large memory and due to less expensive RAM.
[src:aws-elasticache/in-memory-database] A potential technical hurdle with in-memory data storage is the volatility of RAM.
[src:aws-elasticache/in-memory-database] Specifically in the event of a power loss, intentional or otherwise, data stored in volatile RAM is lost.
[src:aws-elasticache/in-memory-database] With the introduction of non-volatile random-access memory technology, in-memory databases will be able to run at full speed and maintain data in the event of power failure.
[src:aws-elasticache/in-memory-database] In its simplest form, main memory databases store data on volatile memory devices.
[src:aws-elasticache/in-memory-database] These devices lose all stored information when the device loses power or is reset.
[src:aws-elasticache/in-memory-database] In this case, IMDBs can be said to lack support for the "durability" portion of the ACID (atomicity, consistency, isolation, durability) properties.
[src:aws-elasticache/in-memory-database] Volatile memory-based IMDBs can, and often do, support the other three ACID properties of atomicity, consistency and isolation.
[src:aws-elasticache/in-memory-database] While storing data in-memory confers performance advantages, it is an expensive method of data storage.
[src:aws-elasticache/in-memory-database] An approach to realising the benefits of in-memory storage while limiting its costs is to store the most frequently accessed data in-memory and the rest on disk.
[src:aws-elasticache/in-memory-database] Since there is no hard distinction between which data should be stored in-memory and which should be stored on disk, some systems dynamically update where data is stored based on the data's usage.
[src:aws-elasticache/in-memory-database] This approach is subtly different from caching, in which the most *recently accessed* data is cached, as opposed to the most *frequently accessed* data being stored in-memory.
[src:aws-elasticache/in-memory-database] In the cloud computing industry the terms "data temperature", or "hot data" and "cold data" have emerged to describe how data is stored in this respect.
[src:aws-elasticache/in-memory-database] Hot data is used to describe mission-critical data that needs to be accessed frequently while cold data describes data that is needed less often and less urgently, such as data kept for archiving or auditing purposes.
[src:aws-elasticache/in-memory-database] Hot data should be stored in ways offering fast retrieval and modification, often accomplished by in-memory storage but not always.
[src:aws-elasticache/in-memory-database] Cold data on the other hand can be stored in a more cost-effective way and is accepted that data access will likely be slower compared to hot data.
[src:aws-elasticache/in-memory-database] While these descriptions are useful, "hot" and "cold" lack concrete definitions.
[src:aws-elasticache/in-memory-database] Manufacturing efficiency provides another reason for selecting a combined in-memory/on-disk database system.
[src:aws-elasticache/in-memory-database] Some device product lines, especially in consumer electronics, include some units with permanent storage, and others that rely on memory for storage (set-top boxes, for example).
[src:aws-elasticache/in-memory-database] If such devices require a database system, a manufacturer can adopt a hybrid database system at lower and *upper* cost, and with less customization of code, rather than using separate in-memory and on-disk databases, respectively, for its disk-less and disk-based products.
[src:aws-elasticache/in-memory-database] The first database engine to support both in-memory and on-disk tables in a single database, WebDNA, was released in 1995.
[src:aws-elasticache/in-memory-database] Another variation involves large amounts of nonvolatile memory in the server, for example, flash memory chips as addressable memory rather than structured as disk arrays.
[src:aws-elasticache/in-memory-database] A database in this form of memory combines very fast access speed with persistence over reboots and power losses.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] Latency is physically a consequence of the limited velocity at which any physical interaction can propagate.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] The magnitude of this velocity is always less than or equal to the speed of light.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] Therefore, every physical system with any physical separation (distance) between cause and effect will experience some sort of latency, regardless of the nature of the stimulation to which it has been exposed.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] The precise definition of latency depends on the system being observed or the nature of the simulation.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] In communications, the lower limit of latency is determined by the medium being used to transfer information.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] In reliable two-way communication systems, latency limits the maximum rate at which information can be transmitted, as there is often a limit on the amount of information that is in-flight at any given moment.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] Perceptible latency has a strong effect on user satisfaction and usability in the field of human–machine interaction.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] Online games are sensitive to latency (lag), since fast response times to new events occurring during a game session are rewarded while slow response times may carry penalties.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] Due to a delay in transmission of game events, a player with a high-latency internet connection may show slow responses in spite of appropriate reaction time.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] This gives players with low-latency connections a technical advantage.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] Trading using computers has developed to the point where millisecond improvements in network speeds offer a competitive advantage for financial institutions.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] However, in a non-trivial network, a typical packet will be forwarded over multiple links and gateways, each of which will not begin to forward the packet until it has been completely received.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] In such a network, the minimal latency is the sum of the transmission delay of each link, plus the forwarding latency of each gateway.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] In practice, minimal latency also includes queuing and processing delays.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] Queuing delay occurs when a gateway receives multiple packets from different sources heading toward the same destination.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] Since typically only one packet can be transmitted at a time, some of the packets must queue for transmission, incurring additional delay.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] Processing delays are incurred while a gateway determines what to do with a newly received packet.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] Bufferbloat can also cause increased latency that is an order of magnitude or more.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] The combination of propagation, serialization, queuing, and processing delays often produces a complex and variable network latency profile.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] Latency limits total throughput in reliable two-way communication systems as described by the bandwidth-delay product.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] Latency in optical fiber is largely a function of the speed of light.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] This would equate to a latency of 3.33 μs for every kilometer of path length.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] The index of refraction of most fiber optic cables is about 1.5, meaning that light travels about 1.5 times as fast in a vacuum as it does in the cable.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] This works out to about 5.0 μs of latency for every kilometer.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] In shorter metro networks, higher latency can be experienced due to extra distance in building risers and cross-connects.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] To calculate the latency of a connection, one has to know the distance traveled by the fiber, which is rarely a straight line, since it has to traverse geographic contours and obstacles, such as roads and railway tracks, as well as other rights-of-way.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] Due to imperfections in the fiber, light degrades as it is transmitted through it.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] For distances of greater than 100 kilometers, amplifiers or regenerators are deployed.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] Latency introduced by these components needs to be taken into account.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] Low Earth orbit is sometimes used to cut this delay, at the expense of more complicated satellite tracking on the ground and requiring more satellites in the satellite constellation to ensure continuous coverage.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] Audio latency is the delay between when an audio signal enters and when it emerges from a system.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] Potential contributors to latency in an audio system include analog-to-digital conversion, buffering, digital signal processing, transmission time, digital-to-analog conversion and the speed of sound in air.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] Video latency refers to the degree of delay between the time a transfer of a video stream is requested and the actual time that transfer begins.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] Networks that exhibit relatively small delays are known as low-latency networks, while their counterparts are known as high-latency networks.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] Any individual workflow within a system of workflows can be subject to some type of operational latency.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] It may even be the case that an individual system may have more than one type of latency, depending on the type of participant or goal-seeking behavior.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] This is best illustrated by the following two examples involving air travel.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] From the point of view of a passenger, latency can be described as follows.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] Suppose John Doe flies from London to New York.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] The latency of his trip is the time it takes him to go from his house in England to the hotel he is staying at in New York.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] This is independent of the throughput of the London-New York air link, whether there were 100 passengers a day making the trip or 10000, the latency of the trip would remain the same.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] From the point of view of flight operations personnel, latency can be entirely different.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] Consider the staff at the London and New York airports.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] Only a limited number of planes are able to make the transatlantic journey, so when one lands, they must prepare it for the return trip as quickly as possible.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] However, cleaning, refueling and loading the cargo can be done at the same time.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] Passengers can only be loaded after cleaning is complete.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] The people involved in the turnaround are interested only in the time it takes for their individual tasks.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] When all of the tasks are done at the same time, however, it is possible to reduce the latency to the length of the longest task.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] If some steps have prerequisites, it becomes more difficult to perform all steps in parallel.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] In the example above, the requirement to clean the plane before loading passengers results in a minimum latency longer than any single task.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] Any mechanical process encounters limitations modeled by Newtonian physics.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] The behavior of disk drives provides an example of mechanical latency.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] Here, it is the time seek time for the actuator arm to be positioned above the appropriate track and then rotational latency for the data encoded on a platter to rotate from its current position to a position under the disk read-and-write head.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] Computers run instructions in the context of a process.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] In the context of computer multitasking, the execution of the process can be postponed if other processes are also executing.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] In addition, the operating system can schedule when to perform the action that the process is commanding.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] For example, suppose a process commands that a computer card's voltage output be set high-low-high-low and so on at a rate of 1000 Hz.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] The operating system schedules the process for each transition (high-low or low-high) based on a hardware clock, such as the High Precision Event Timer.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] The latency is the delay between the events generated by the hardware clock and the actual transitions of voltage from high to low or low to high.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] Many desktop operating systems have performance limitations that create additional latency.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] The problem may be mitigated with real-time extensions and patches such as PREEMPT RT.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] On embedded systems, the real-time execution of instructions is often supported by a real-time operating system.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] Note that in software systems, benchmarking against *average* and *median* latency can be misleading because a few outliers can distort them.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] Instead, software architects and software developers should use "99th percentile".
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] In simulation applications, latency refers to the time delay, often measured in milliseconds, between initial input and output clearly discernible to the simulator trainee or simulator subject.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] Latency is sometimes also called *transport delay*.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] Some authorities distinguish between latency and transport delay by using the term *latency* in the sense of the extra time delay of a system over and above the reaction time of the vehicle being simulated, but this requires detailed knowledge of the vehicle dynamics and can be controversial.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] In simulators with both visual and motion systems, it is particularly important that the latency of the motion system not be greater than of the visual system, or symptoms of simulator sickness may result.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] This is because, in the real world, motion cues are those of acceleration and are quickly transmitted to the brain, typically in less than 50 milliseconds; this is followed some milliseconds later by a perception of change in the visual scene.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] The visual scene change is essentially one of change of perspective or displacement of objects, such as the horizon, which takes some time to build up to discernible amounts after the initial acceleration that caused the displacement.
[src:aws-elasticache/latency-engineering] A simulator should, therefore, reflect the real-world situation by ensuring that the motion latency is equal to or less than that of the visual system and not the other way round.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] In computing **Memcached** (pronounced either /mɛmkæʃˈdiː/ *mem-cash-DEE* ["dee/d" being for daemon], or /ˈmɛmkæʃt/ *MEM-cashed*) is a general-purpose distributed memory-caching system.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] It is often used to speed up dynamic database-driven websites by caching data and objects in RAM to reduce the number of times an external data source (such as a database or API) must be read.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] Memcached is free and open-source software, licensed under the Revised BSD license.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] Memcached runs on Unix-like operating systems (Linux and macOS) and on Microsoft Windows.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] Memcached's APIs provide a large hash table distributed across multiple machines.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] When the table is full, subsequent inserts cause older data to be purged in least recently used (LRU) order.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] Applications using Memcached typically layer requests and additions into RAM before falling back on a slower backing store, such as a database.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] Memcached has no internal mechanism to track misses which may happen.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] However, some third party utilities provide this functionality.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] Memcached was first developed by Brad Fitzpatrick for his website LiveJournal, on May 22, 2003.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] It was originally written in Perl, then later rewritten in C by Anatoly Vorobey, who was employed by LiveJournal at the time.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] Memcached is now used by many other systems, including YouTube, Reddit, Facebook, Pinterest, Twitter, Wikipedia, and Method Studios.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] Google App Engine, Google Cloud Platform, Microsoft Azure, IBM Bluemix and Amazon Web Services also offer a Memcached service through an API.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] The system uses a client–server architecture.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] The servers maintain a key–value associative array; the clients populate this array and query it by key.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] Keys are up to 250 bytes long and values can be at most 1 megabyte in size.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] Clients use client-side libraries to contact the servers which, by default, expose their service at port 11211.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] Each client knows all servers; the servers do not communicate with each other.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] If a client wishes to set or read the value corresponding to a certain key, the client's library first computes a hash of the key to determine which server to use.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] This gives a simple form of sharding and scalable shared-nothing architecture across the servers.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] The server computes a second hash of the key to determine where to store or read the corresponding value.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] The servers keep the values in RAM (and, starting in 1.6.0, in auxiliary cache on disk using an external storage server option); if a server runs out of available memory or disk, it discards the oldest values.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] Therefore, clients must treat Memcached as a transitory cache; they cannot assume that data stored in Memcached is still there when they need it.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] Other databases, such as MemcacheDB, Couchbase Server, provide persistent storage while maintaining Memcached protocol compatibility.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] If all client libraries use the same hashing algorithm to determine servers, then clients can read each other's cached data.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] A typical deployment has several servers and many clients.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] However, it is possible to use Memcached on a single computer, acting simultaneously as client and server.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] The size of its hash table is often very large.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] It is limited to available memory across all the servers in the cluster of servers in a data center.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] Where high-volume, wide-audience Web publishing requires it, this may stretch to many gigabytes.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] Memcached can be equally valuable for situations where either the number of requests for content is high, or the cost of generating a particular piece of content is high.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] Applications with particularly high-demand caching needs can use a built-in proxy to define and configure complex client-server routes.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] Most deployments of Memcached are within trusted networks where clients may freely connect to any server.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] However, sometimes Memcached is deployed in untrusted networks or where administrators want to exercise control over the clients that are connecting.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] For this purpose Memcached can be compiled with optional SASL authentication support.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] The SASL support requires the binary protocol.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] A presentation at BlackHat USA 2010 revealed that a number of large public websites had left Memcached open to inspection, analysis, retrieval, and modification of data.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] Even within a trusted organisation, the flat trust model of memcached may have security implications.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] For efficient simplicity, all Memcached operations are treated equally.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] Clients with a valid need for access to low-security entries within the cache gain access to *all* entries within the cache, even when these are higher-security and that client has no justifiable need for them.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] If the cache key can be either predicted, guessed or found by exhaustive searching, its cache entry may be retrieved.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] Some attempt to isolate setting and reading data may be made in situations such as high volume web publishing.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] A farm of outward-facing content servers have *read* access to memcached containing published pages or page components, but no write access.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] Where new content is published (and is not yet in memcached), a request is instead sent to content generation servers that are not publicly accessible to create the content unit and add it to memcached.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] The content server then retries to retrieve it and serve it outwards.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] In February 2018, CloudFlare reported that misconfigured memcached servers were used to launch DDoS attacks in large scale.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] The memcached protocol over UDP has a huge amplification factor, of more than 51000.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] Victims of the DDoS attacks include GitHub, which was flooded with 1.35 Tbit/s peak incoming traffic.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] This issue was mitigated in Memcached version 1.5.6, which disabled UDP protocol by default.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] Converting database or object creation queries to use Memcached is simple.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] The client would first check whether a Memcached value with the unique key "userrow:userid" exists, where userid is some number.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] If the result does not exist, it would select from the database as usual, and set the unique key using the Memcached API add function call.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] However, if only this API call were modified, the server would end up fetching incorrect data following any database update actions: the Memcached "view" of the data would become out of date.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] Therefore, in addition to creating an "add" call, an update call would also be needed using the Memcached set function.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] This call would update the currently cached data to match the new data in the database, assuming the database query succeeds.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] An alternative approach would be to invalidate the cache with the Memcached delete function, so that subsequent fetches result in a cache miss.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] Similar action would need to be taken when database records were deleted, to maintain either a correct or incomplete cache.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] An alternate cache-invalidation strategy is to store a random number in an agreed-upon cache entry and to incorporate this number into all keys that are used to store a particular kind of entry.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] To invalidate all such entries at once, change the random number.
[src:aws-elasticache/memcached] Existing entries (which were stored using the old number) will no longer be referenced and so will eventually expire or be recycled.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] The project was developed and maintained by Salvatore Sanfilippo, starting in 2009.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] From 2015 until 2020, he led a project core team sponsored by Redis Labs.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] Salvatore Sanfilippo left Redis as the maintainer in 2020.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] In 2021 Redis Labs dropped the Labs from its name and now is known simply as "Redis".
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] In 2018, some modules for Redis adopted a modified Apache 2.0 license with a Commons Clause.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] In 2024, the main Redis code switched from the open-source BSD-3 license to being dual-licensed under the Redis Source Available License v2 and the Server Side Public License v1.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] On May 1, 2025, Redis became tri-licensed beginning with version 8.0, with the GNU Affero General Public License as the third option.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] The name *Redis* means Remote Dictionary Server.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] The Redis project began when Salvatore Sanfilippo (nicknamed *antirez*) was trying to improve the scalability of his Italian startup and developed a real-time web log analyzer.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] After encountering significant problems in scaling some types of workloads using traditional database systems, Sanfilippo began in 2009 to prototype a first proof of concept version of Redis in Tcl.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] Later, Sanfilippo translated that prototype to the C language and implemented the first data type, the list.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] After a few weeks of using the project internally with success, Sanfilippo decided to open source it, announcing the project on Hacker News.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] The project began to get traction, particularly among the Ruby community, with GitHub and Instagram being among the first companies adopting it.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] Sanfilippo was hired by VMware in March 2010.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] In May 2013, Redis was sponsored by Pivotal Software (a VMware spin-off).
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] In June 2015, development became sponsored by Redis Ltd.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] This made the modules source-available and no longer free software.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] The core Redis software remained under a BSD license, with Redis Ltd. committing to maintaining these terms.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] In October 2018, Redis 5.0 was released, introducing Redis Stream – a new data structure that allows storage of multiple fields and string values with an automatic, time-based sequence at a single key.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] In June 2020, Salvatore Sanfilippo stepped down as Redis' sole maintainer.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] Sanfilippo was succeeded by Yossi Gottlieb and Oran Agra.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] In March 2024, Redis Ltd. announced that beginning with version 7.4, the core Redis software would be relicensed under the RSAL and Server Side Public License (SSPL), both of which are source-available and non-free.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] The Linux Foundation subsequently announced that it would fork the last BSD-licensed version of Redis as Valkey.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] In May 2025, Redis Ltd. announced that it would change the license again to the AGPL beginning on version 8.0, citing that forks had achieved their goal of creating a "level playing field" of differentiated products, and that Redis has achieved "record growth" since the change in license.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] Sanfilippo returned to Redis in December 2024.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] Redis is a system that functions as both a data store and a cache.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] Data is modified and read from the main computer memory while also being persisted to disk in a format optimized for sequential access rather than random access.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] The formatted data is only reconstructed into memory once the system restarts.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] Redis uses a data model that differs from relational database management system (RDBMS).
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] Commands specify operations on abstract data types rather than queries to be executed by a database engine.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] Data is stored in structures designed for direct retrieval.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] It does not rely on secondary indexes, aggregations, or other features common in traditional RDBMS.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] The Redis implementation uses the fork system call to duplicate the process holding the data.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] This allows the parent process to continue serving clients while the child process persists the in-memory data to disk.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] Redis supports a number of data types including Strings, JavaScript Object Notation (JSON) documents, Hashes (a collection of fields, each field is a name-value string pair), lists, sets, vector sets, and more.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] The Redis Query Engine allows users to use Redis as a document database, a vector database, a secondary index, and a search engine.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] With Redis Query Engine, users can define indexes for hash and JSON documents, and use a rich query language for vector search, full-text search, geospatial queries, and aggregations.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] Redis Pub/Sub (short for publish/subscribe) is a lightweight messaging capability.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] Publishers send messages to a channel, and subscribers receive messages from that channel.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] A Redis transaction allows the execution of a group of commands in a single step.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] A request sent by another client will never be served during the execution of a transaction.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] This guarantees that the commands are executed as a single isolated operation.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] Redis users can also upload and execute Lua scripts on the server.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] As of May 1, 2025, for all version of Redis starting with 8.0, all data types are included in the same package and available under the Redis Source Available license v2.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] Previously some data types were separate and therefore available under difference licenses.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] Redis typically holds the whole dataset in memory.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] Versions up to 2.4 could be configured to use what they refer to as virtual memory in which some of the dataset is stored on disk, but this feature is deprecated.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] Redis can rewrite the append-only file in the background to avoid an indefinite growth of the journal.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] Journaling was introduced in version 1.1 and is generally considered the safer approach.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] By default, Redis writes data to a file system at least every two seconds, with more or less robust options available if needed.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] In the case of a complete system failure on default settings, only a few seconds of data will be lost.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] Redis supports master–replica replication.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] Data from any Redis server can replicate to any number of replicas.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] A replica may be a master to another replica.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] This allows Redis to implement a single-rooted replication tree.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] Redis replicas can be configured to accept writes, permitting intentional and unintentional inconsistency between instances.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] The publish–subscribe feature is fully implemented, so a client of a replica may subscribe to a channel and receive a full feed of messages published to the master, anywhere up the replication tree.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] Replication is useful for read (but not write) scalability or data redundancy.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] When the durability of data is not needed, the in-memory nature of Redis allows it to perform well compared to database systems that write every change to disk before considering a transaction committed.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] Redis operates as a single process and is single-threaded or double-threaded when it rewrites the AOF (append-only file).
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] Thus, a single Redis instance cannot use parallel execution of tasks such as stored procedures.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] Redis introduced clustering in April 2015 with the release of version 3.0.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] The cluster specification implements a subset of Redis commands: all single-key commands are available, multi-key operations (commands related to unions and intersections) are restricted to keys belonging to the same node, and commands related to database selection operations are unavailable.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] A Redis cluster can scale up to 1,000 nodes, achieve "acceptable" write safety and to continue operations when some nodes fail.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] Redis has been used by Adobe, Airbnb, Amazon, Hulu, OpenAI, Salesforce, Shopify, Tinder, Twitter, and Yahoo.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] Typical use cases of Redis are session caching, full page cache, message queue applications, leaderboards and counting among others.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] The publish–subscribe messaging paradigm allows real-time communication between servers.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] Amazon Web Services offers a managed Redis service called ElastiCache for Redis, Google offers a managed Redis service called Cloud Memorystore, Microsoft offers Azure Cache for Redis in Azure, and Alibaba offers ApsaraDB for Redis in Alibaba Cloud.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] Redis is interfaced with by various libraries.
[src:aws-elasticache/redis] For example, POCO C++ Libraries supports interfacing with Redis through its `Poco::Redis` library.
